From: Sungjoon Moon <sumoon@seoulsaram.org>
Date: Thu, 26 Jun 2026 02:30:00 +0900
Subject: [PATCH] hwclock: fall back to libc settimeofday on time64-only ABIs

Linux 6.x architectures that ship as time64-only from the start (riscv32,
arc HS, etc.) expose neither SYS_settimeofday nor SYS_settimeofday_time32
in <asm/unistd.h>; settimeofday was never given a *_time64 variant because
clock_settime64() supersedes it.  The existing musl-special-case raw
syscall therefore fails to compile:

  util-linux/hwclock.c:143:27: error: 'SYS_settimeofday' undeclared

Fall back to the libc wrapper when no syscall number exists.  Under musl
this loses the timezone argument (which is exactly the bug the raw-syscall
path was working around) but compiles and does not crash — and on these
new ABIs there is no other option short of open-coding the timezone shim.

Signed-off-by: Sungjoon Moon <sumoon@seoulsaram.org>
---
 util-linux/hwclock.c | 4 ++++
 1 file changed, 4 insertions(+)

diff --git a/util-linux/hwclock.c b/util-linux/hwclock.c
--- a/util-linux/hwclock.c
+++ b/util-linux/hwclock.c
@@ -140,7 +140,11 @@ static void set_kernel_tz(const struct timezone *tz)
 #if !defined(SYS_settimeofday) && defined(SYS_settimeofday_time32)
 # define SYS_settimeofday SYS_settimeofday_time32
 #endif
+#ifdef SYS_settimeofday
 	int ret = syscall(SYS_settimeofday, NULL, tz);
+#else
+	int ret = settimeofday(NULL, tz);
+#endif
 #else
 	int ret = settimeofday(NULL, tz);
 #endif
--
2.47.0
